The Acherusian Chersonese is likely a lake, swamp, or cavern where, as Xenophon notes, Heracles is said to have descended after Cerberus. It's exact location is ambiguous, but given that it is in or very near Heracleia, it is located using the city's Pleiades reference point as a proxy.

Xenophon identities the area from the Bosphorus to Heracleia Pontus as 'Thrace-in-Asia'. He seems to be the only classical author to make this distinction, as this region is typically northwestern Bythinia.

Xenophon seems to distinguish 'Bythinian Thracians' as a unique ethnic group among the peoples of Bythinia. However, this carries similar difficulties to the annotation on 'Thrace-in-Asia' for conflating it with a Pleiades ID or map location, though in this instance there is Wikidata available.

See extended commentary for a full analysis, but this Spithridates may be the same one that fought and died to Alexander the Great, but difference in dates between the events here in the Anabasis and the Battle of Granicus make this improbable (though not impossible). So, we have refrained from concretely confalting the two here.

See extended commentary for a full analysis. Rhathines is a figure who appears to only be mentioned in the Anabasis and in conjunction with Spithridates. There is a very small possibility Xenophon could have misspelled Rhoesaces, the brother of the Spithridates who fought in the Battle of Granicus, but this is highly unlikely. The Greek names are very different (Ῥωσάκης vs  Ῥαθίνης)., and, as mentioned in the annotation on Spithridates, the time gap between the events of the Anabasis and Alexander the Great makes this improbable.|Update: After discussing this in a meeting, there is enough evidence with how Xenophon mentions Spithridates in the text to make a connection with the Spithridates mentioned by Diodorus. Similarly, Rhathines, while a bit more ambiguous due to the different spellings, can be connected to Rhoesaces mentioned by Diodorus and Arrian. Both Diodorus and Arrian already spell Rhoesaces differently (Ῥωσάκην and Ῥοισάκης respectively), so it's not unprecedented for Xenophon, writing at least a couple centuries before either of these, to spell the name differently. Additionally, it there is Wikidata used for Rhathines (under the name Ratines), though it is only used in one article written in Catalan. It may be beneficial to merge the Wikidata for Rhoesaces and Ratines, and update the English page to reflect this.
